title: Standing Dual-Handle Chest Fly
context:
1.Adjust the handles to chest height.
2.Stand in a split stance with core engaged for stability.
3.Grip a handle in each hand and slowly open your arms out to the sides.
4.Exhale while engaging your chest to bring your hands forward for 1–2 seconds, actively squeezing the chest.
5.Inhale and slowly return your hands along the same path to the starting position.

guideVoice4Txt: Keep your arms extended to your sides to fully stretch your chest, with your palms facing each other the entire time

guideVoice6Txt: Engage your pecs to press the handles forward, directly in front of your chest.

title: Standing Dual-Handle Low-to-High Chest Fly
context:
1.Set the pulley to the lowest position and attach the dual handles.
2.Stand in the center of the machine with a stable split stance.
3.Grip a handle in each hand, letting your arms hang naturally at your sides with palms facing forward.
4.Inhale to prepare, then exhale while engaging your chest to bring your hands upward along an arc.

context:

2.Inhale to prepare, then engage your chest to drive the rope downward at an incline. Keep your upper arms contracted against your body, and squeeze for 1 to 2 seconds at the bottom.

title: Barbell Bench Press
context:
1.Lie on a bench, holding the barbell above the chest.
2.From the starting position, slowly lower the barbell to the mid-chest.
3.Drive through the chest and triceps to press the barbell back up to the starting position.

guideVoice3Txt: Pack your shoulders, open your chest, and draw your abdomen in.

title: Incline Barbell Close-Grip Chest Press
context:
1.Set the bench to a 30° incline and lie back.
2.Grip the barbell with hands slightly narrower than shoulder-width.
3.Lower the barbell under control to above the chest, elbows tucked close to the body.
4.Press the barbell up using the chest and triceps until arms are nearly straight, pausing briefly at the top.

breathingRate: Exhale while pressing up, inhale while lowering down.

title: Reverse Narrow Grip Barbell Bench Press
context:
1.Lie on the bench with feet flat on the floor and core engaged.
2.Grip the barbell with a narrow reverse grip, palms facing you.
3.Keep wrists aligned with forearms, barbell starting above your chest.
4.Lower the bar under control to mid or lower chest, elbows close to your body.
5.Press the bar back up vertically using your chest and triceps.

title: Barbell Reverse Grip Bench Press
context:
1.Lie on the bench with feet flat on the floor and core engaged.
2.Grip the barbell with a reverse grip, palms facing you.
3.Lower the barbell to mid-chest or slightly below, keeping elbows close to your body.
4.Press the barbell vertically with control until your arms are nearly straight, without locking your elbows.

title: Standing Single-Arm Chest Press
context:
1.Stand in a staggered stance with core engaged to stabilize the body.
2.Hold the handle with one hand, roughly at chest height.
3.Exhale and press the handle forward along a horizontal line using the chest.
4.Extend the arm without locking the elbow, lightly squeezing the chest.
5.Inhale and slowly return the handle to the starting position.

title: Kneeling Barbell High-to-Low Chest  Press
context: Kneel on both knees with hips-width distance. Keep the torso upright, core engaged, and body stable. Grip the barbell with a wide overhand grip, wrists neutral, palms facing down. Inhale to prepare. As you exhale, press the barbell downward along a high-to-low diagonal path toward the lower chest, focusing on engaging the mid to lower pecs. Inhale as you return to the starting position with control. Allow natural scapular movement throughout—avoid shrugging the shoulders or arching the lower back. Keep the spine straight. Use light to moderate resistance to enhance pressing stability and chest activation.

4.Slowly return to the starting position.

context:

2.Keep the core tight and stable, shoulders depressed.
3.Push the handles upward until the arms are nearly straight.
4.Pause 1–2 seconds at the top, lightly squeezing the chest to fully contract the muscles.
5.Slowly return to the starting position.

context:

3.Exhale, press the bar above the clavicles, elbows nearly straight but not locked.
4.Inhale, slowly lower the bar to the upper chest midline, keeping elbows pointing down.

title: Kneeling Dual-Handle High-to-Low Chest Press
context: Kneel on both knees with hips-width distance. Tops of the feet flat or toes tucked under. Keep the pelvis neutral, core engaged, and torso upright and stable. Grip the handles on both sides with neutral wrists, palms facing down, and a slight bend in the elbows. Inhale to prepare. As you exhale, press both hands forward and downward along a high-to-low diagonal path toward the lower chest, focusing on the contraction of the mid to lower pectoral muscles. Maintain a smooth and steady tempo to enhance chest stability and pressing power.

1.Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, core engaged.
2.Hold the barbell overhand, hands just wider than shoulders, arms relaxed in front of thighs.
3.Lift the barbell in a controlled straight line to shoulder height or slightly above.
4.Pause at the top for 1–2 seconds, focusing on the shoulder contraction.
5.Lower the barbell under control, avoiding a rapid drop.
showDetails: [{"context":"1.Keep the shoulder girdle depressed.\n2.Maintain a slight bend in the knees.\n3.Hold a neutral spine position.","img":"https://d1rwzqjevxdih5.cloudfront.net/1748317792651.jpg"},{"context":"1.Keep a slight bend in the elbows.","img":"https://d1rwzqjevxdih5.cloudfront.net/1748317800193.jpg"}]

motionFeeling: Engage the deltoids.
errorCorrection: Keep the shoulders depressed throughout the lift, avoiding shrugging.
guideVoice1Txt: Lock the pulleys to the floor with the barbell attached.
guideVoice2Txt: Stand tall with your knees slightly bent and your grip shoulder-width apart.
guideVoice3Txt: Keep your core engaged and tight.
guideVoice4Txt: Don’t let your body momentum take control and reduce the tension.
guideVoice5Txt: Keep breathing. Exhale during the exertion phase and inhale as you return to the starting position.
guideVoice6Txt: Squeeze and contract your deltoid to lift the barbell to eye level.

title: Seated Barbell Shoulder Press
context:
1.Sit on the bench in a neutral position, holding the barbell at shoulder height with an overhand grips.
2.Press the barbell overhead until your arms extended. 
3.Hold at the top for a count of two to feel the muscle contraction.
3.Come back to the start position slowly with nice control.

title: Barbell Bent Over Row
context:
1.Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, and core engaged.
2.Hinge forward 45°–60°, keeping a neutral spine.
3.Grip the barbell overhand, hands shoulder-width or slightly wider.
4.Keep elbows close to your sides and engage your lats.
5.Pull the barbell up along your front to lower chest or abdomen.
6.Pause briefly at the top, then return to the starting position.

title: Kneeling Barbell Lat Pulldown
context:
1.Kneel with your back straight and core engaged.
2.Overhand grip the barbell, hands slightly wider than shoulder-width.
3.Position the bar above your chest, shoulders down and scapulae retracted.
4.Pull the bar down in front of your body to just above your collarbone under control.
5.Keep wrists neutral, elbows pointing down and slightly back.
6.Slowly return the bar to the starting position under control.

title: Standing Barbell Shrugs
context:

2.Grip the barbell with palms facing your body (overhand grip).
3.Let your arms hang naturally and shrug your shoulders up toward your ears.
4.Keep your arms and elbows straight, using only your shoulders to lift.
5.Pause briefly at the top, then slowly return to the starting position.

context:

4.Engage your glutes and hamstrings to extend hips and knees, pulling the barbell up along your thighs.
5.Stand fully upright, tightening your glutes at the top.
6.Unlike straight-leg or Romanian deadlifts, this version focuses more on glute contraction.

title: Standing Cable Kickback（Main Frame）
context:
1.Adjust the grips to the lowest position of the armrest.
2.Face the machine and securely attach the strap to one ankle. Hold onto the machine for support.
3.Stand tall with your feet hip-width apart, toes pointing forward, chest lifted, and back straight. Engage your core for stability.
4.Slowly kick the leg with the strap diagonally backward, keeping the hip joint in a neutral position.

context: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, core braced. Hold a dumbbell in each hand using a neutral grip (palms facing inward), arms hanging naturally at your sides. title: Standing Push Twist
context: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart on one side of the cable machine, knees slightly bent and feet firmly planted. Keep your back straight, chest slightly lifted, and actively engage your core to stabilize your torso. Hold the handle with your arm at your side, using your core and chest muscles to drive the movement. Slowly push the handle forward while rotating your torso to the opposite side. Pause briefly when your arm is almost fully extended or your torso reaches its rotational limit, feeling the contraction in your obliques and chest muscles. Then, slowly return to the starting position. Exhale while pushing, inhale while returning. Throughout the movement, maintain a straight lower back and avoid compensating by bending or arching your back.

Initiate the movement from your core, as both hands together bring the handle along a diagonal path downward to one side, while rotating your upper body. title: Dual-Handle Thruster
context:

2.Grip the handles with a parallel grip, slightly wider than shoulder-width.
3.Stand with your feet slightly wider than hip-width apart, with toes pointing slightly outward.
4.Keeping your chest up, push your knees forward and your hips slightly back.
5.Lower your body with the goal of sitting between your feet.
6.Lower until your quads are just below horizontal.
7.Drive through your heels to stand up while simultaneously initiating a shoulder press.
8.Start with the handles at shoulder level, elbows pointed downward.
9.Press the handles upward to fully extend your arms overhead.
10.Try to avoid shrugging your shoulders at the top position.
